 <setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="2" to="4" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="1" to="4" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="c" from="1" to="4" step="1"/>
  
  <function name="gprime" symbolic="false" >
    1/$a*(x-$b)^2-$c
    <label><m>g'</m></label>
  </function>

  <function name="L" symbolic="false" >
    $$g($a) + $$gprime($a)*(x-$a)
    <label><m>L</m></label>
  </function>
  
  <derivative name="gPP" symbolic="false">
    $gprime
  </derivative>  
      
  <point name="A" styleNumber="2"> 
    <constraints>      
      <attractToGrid dx="0.5" />
      <constrainTo>$gprime</constrainTo>
    </constraints>
    <label>A</label>
  </point>
  
<!-- <function domain="($xA-1,$xA+1)">$m1*(x-$x1)^2+$y1</function> -->
  
  <function name="f" symbolic="true">-1/3*x^3 + $a*x^2 - 2*$b*x + 2*$a + $b</function>
  <derivative name="fP" symbolic="true">$f </derivative>
  <derivative name="fPP" symbolic="true">$fP </derivative>

</setup>

    <p>
      Let <m>g</m> be a differentiable function whose <em>derivative</em>, <m>g'</m> is given  in the figure below.
    </p>  

      <graph xmin="-1" xmax="5" ymin="-5" ymax="5" size="medium" grid="true" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true"> 
        $gprime 
        $A  
        <label anchor="(2.5,$$gprime(2)-0.5)"><m>y = g'(x)</m> </label>
      </graph>

    <p>
      Again, note that the given graph is <m>y = g'(x)</m>. You can drag point <m>A</m> along the graph of <m>y = g'(x)</m> and see the point's coordinates as you move it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suppose we are interested in approximating values of <m>g(x)</m> near <m>x = $a</m>, and we know that <m>g($a) = $b</m>.
    </p>

<!--
  <p>
    Testing: <m>a = $a, b = $b, c = $c, g(a) = $b, g'(a) = $$gprime($a)</m>
  </p>
-->

    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>Based on the given graph, what is the value of <m>g'($a)</m>?</p>
        <p><m>g'($a) = </m>
          <answer>
            <award allowedErrorInNumbers="0.1" allowedErrorIsAbsolute> $$gprime($a)
            </award>
          </answer>
        </p>
      </li>  
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine a formula for <m>L(x)</m>, the tangent line approximation to <m>y = g(x)</m> at the point <m>($a, g($a))</m>.  
        </p>
<!--        
        <p> <m>L(x) = </m><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.02" allowedErrorIsAbsolute>
          $b + $$gprime($a)*(x-$a)
        </answer> </p>  
-->

        <p>
          <m>L(x) = </m> <mathInput minWidth="100" name="Lx"></mathInput>
          <answer  allowedErrorInNumbers="0.02" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award><when>$Lx = ($b + $$gprime($a)*(x-$a))</when></award> </answer>
        </p>
        
    <!--    Testing:  <m>L(x) = <math>$b + $$gprime($a)*(x-$a)</math></m> -->
        
      </li>  
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the tangent line approximation you found in (b) to estimate <math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math>.
        </p>      
        <p>
          <m><math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math> \approx</m> <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.02" allowedErrorIsAbsolute>$b + $$gprime($a)*(0.05*$c) </answer>
        </p>  
      </li>  
      <li>
        <p>
          How is the estimate of <math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math> that you found in (c) likely related to the true value of <math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math>?
          <choiceInput name="menu">
            <choice>greater than</choice>
            <choice>less than</choice>
            <choice>equal to</choice>
            <choice>not enough information to say</choice>  
          </choiceInput>   
          <answer>
            <award>
              <when>$menu.selectedIndices=1 and $$gPP($a) < 0 </when>
            </award>  
            <award>
              <when>$menu.selectedIndices=2 and $$gPP($a) > 0 </when>
            </award>
            <award>
              <when>$menu.selectedIndices=4 and $$gPP($a) = 0 </when> 
            </award>
          </answer>

        </p>  
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          One reason that the estimate the tangent line approximation provides for <math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math> is     <answer>
          <choiceInput name="choice1" inline>
            <choice>greater than</choice>
            <choice>less than</choice>
            <choice>equal to</choice>
            <choice>insufficient to determine</choice>  
          </choiceInput>            
            <award>
              <when>$choice1.selectedIndices=1 and $$gPP($a) < 0       
              </when>
            </award>  
            <award>
              <when>$choice1.selectedIndices=2 and $$gPP($a) > 0 
              </when>
            </award>
            <award>
              <when>$choice1.selectedIndices=4 and $$gPP($a) = 0 
              </when> 
            </award>
    </answer>
    the true value of  <math simplify>g($a+0.05*$c)</math> is because 
  <answer>
          <choiceInput name="choice2" inline>
            <choice>g($a)</choice>
            <choice>g'($a)</choice>
            <choice credit="1">g''($a)</choice>
            <choice>L($a)</choice>  
          </choiceInput>            
    </answer>  
    is
  <answer>
          <choiceInput name="choice3" inline>
            <choice>negative</choice>
            <choice>zero</choice>
            <choice>positive</choice>
          </choiceInput>            
            <award>
              <when>$choice3.selectedIndices=1 and $$gPP($a) < 0    
              </when>
            </award>  
            <award>
              <when>$choice3.selectedIndices=2 and $$gPP($a) = 0 
              </when>
            </award>
            <award>
              <when>$choice3.selectedIndices=3 and $$gPP($a) > 0 
              </when> 
            </award>
    </answer>   
    which means that near <m>x = $a</m>, the original function <m>g</m> is 
  <answer>
          <choiceInput name="choice4" inline>
            <choice>concave up</choice>
            <choice>linear</choice>
            <choice>concave down</choice>
          </choiceInput>            
            <award>
              <when>$choice4.selectedIndices=3 and $$gPP($a) < 0    
              </when>
            </award>  
            <award>
              <when>$choice4.selectedIndices=2 and $$gPP($a) = 0 
              </when>
            </award>
            <award>
              <when>$choice4.selectedIndices=1 and $$gPP($a) > 0 
              </when> 
            </award>
    </answer> 
    and this means that the tangent line to <m>g</m> at the point <m>($a,g($a))</m> lies
   <answer>
          <choiceInput name="choice5" inline>
            <choice>below</choice>
            <choice>above</choice>
          </choiceInput>            
            <award>
              <when>$choice5.selectedIndices=2 and $$gPP($a) < 0    
              </when>
            </award>  
            <award>
              <when>$choice5.selectedIndices=1 and $$gPP($a) > 0 
              </when> 
            </award>
    </answer>   
    the curve.
        </p>
      </li>          
    </ol>
  